  "text": "Of course, any good macroeconomic model has to be dynamic and stochastic, and present an analysis of the entire economy. But specific assumptions, as we have noted, went into each of these components. We have already discussed several aspects of the assumed dynamics. 65 For a discussion of some of the recent empirical evidence, see [CITATION_1] . 66 A conjecture, which we noted, turned out to be false whenever there were imperfect risk markets and asymmetric information, except in the very special conditions underlying real business cycle theory and its descendants. 67 For an excellent discussion of these two contrasting views of human nature and their implications for economics, see [CITATION_2] . For an attempt to incorporate some aspects of these considerations into a formal model, see [CITATION_3] .",
